message.content:
{
    "reasoning": "While moving up the red-lit staircase, the companion NPC (Ashley Williams) repeatedly enters a rigid ‘jump/run’ cycle and floats off the steps instead of walking. Her arms stay splayed, legs remain extended in mid-air, and she slides up the stairs in a continuous animation loop that isn’t consistent with normal navmesh or stair-climbing behavior.",
    "bug_report_title": "Companion NPC Floats and Repeats Jump Animation on Stairs",
    "bug_report_description": "When Shepard and squadmates ascend the corridor stairs, Ashley Williams becomes stuck in a T-pose-style jump/run animation. Instead of stepping, she hovers above the steps with her arms outstretched and legs fully extended, sliding upward in place. This occurs repeatedly, preventing normal movement and blocking conversation prompts (‘Talk’). It appears to be a collision or navmesh issue on the staircase geometry that fails to trigger the proper walking or stair-climbing animations. The glitch breaks immersion and could prevent mission progression if the NPC cannot be correctly positioned.",
    "affected_item": "Companion AI animation / physics (Ashley Williams)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "An enemy mammoth has spawned high above the terrain, remains targetable but passes through trees and geometry as it free-falls with no solid collision. The creature repositions abruptly and clips through the world rather than standing or walking on the ground.",
    "bug_report_title": "Mammoth NPC Spawns Floating and Falls Through World Geometry",
    "bug_report_description": "During gameplay the mammoth creature unexpectedly appears in midair above the tree line. It drops through the environment, clipping straight through trees and rocks without collision, then finally lands far below. The mammoth remains targetable (crosshair and health bar visible) but is invulnerable to arrows until it reaches inaccessible terrain. This break in expected AI pathing and physics can confuse the player, block quest progression, and break immersion.",
    "affected_item": "NPC physics/AI (creature spawn and collision)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "After completing the frisk interaction, the player-character’s animation system fails to transition cleanly. Instead of standing up and walking away, the officer model contorts into a seated/floating pose at the curb, repeatedly looping portions of the frisk animation. Limbs bend unnaturally and the character appears to hover and slide without proper collision with the environment.",
    "bug_report_title": "Officer Animation/Ragdoll Glitch Leaves Character Floating and Looping at Curb",
    "bug_report_description": "When finishing the frisk sequence near the bus at Vespucci Blvd, the player-controlled officer does not return to a normal idle or walking state. Instead:\n- The officer collapses into a partially seated posture in mid-air above the curb.\n- Arms and legs contort and stutter, looping segments of the frisk animation.\n- The character model hovers and slides without proper ground collision.\n- No transition to ragdoll physics or proper animation blend-out occurs, leaving the player stuck in the glitch state.\nThis breaks immersion and can block further input, requiring a reload or reset to recover normal movement.",
    "affected_item": "Character animation/physics"
}

{
  "reasoning": "When the pedestrian NPC enters the scene, its model immediately collapses into a weird ragdoll state: limbs hyperextend, the body twists unnaturally, and the character phases into the road surface before sliding along it instead of walking normally.",
  "bug_report_title": "NPC Pedestrian Ragdoll/Collision Glitch Causes Distorted Limbs and Ground Phasing",
  "bug_report_description": "Upon spawning or pathfinding into view, the pedestrian model fails to transition to a proper walk animation, triggering a broken ragdoll with arms and legs stretching through the torso. The character also penetrates the road mesh and slides across the pavement in a seated/crawling pose. This visual and physics anomaly not only breaks immersion but risks blocking sidewalks, disrupting NPC traffic flows, and could potentially halt mission triggers tied to pedestrian interactions.",
  "affected_item": "NPC character model and physics (ragdoll and collision system)"
}

{
  "reasoning": "When the NPC passenger climbs in and out of the driver’s truck, their head and hair geometry—and the cab’s hanging mirror assembly—clip through the roof and windshield, detach, and float independently. The meshes are not parented or occluded correctly, causing parts of the character and accessory to become flat, broken objects in view.",
  "bug_report_title": "Passenger Character & Interior Mirror Mesh Clipping/Detachment",
  "bug_report_description": "During vehicle entry and exit animations, the NPC passenger’s head/hair mesh clips through the cab roof and windshield instead of remaining inside the seat frame. Simultaneously, the hanging mirror accessory detaches and renders as disembodied black polygons, pivoting strangely in the player’s field of view. These broken meshes float and flicker, obstructing sightlines and breaking immersion. The detachment also leaves holes in the model where the mirror should be and prevents proper occlusion of the passenger model.",
  "affected_item": "character model and vehicle interior accessory (rearview mirror)"
}

{  
  "reasoning": "During the cinematic kissing sequence, the female character’s hair strands clip through her own face and the male character’s head, and the hair shader exhibits a noticeable flickering artifact as the frames progress, indicating a transparency/alpha sorting issue.",  
  "bug_report_title": "Hair Mesh Clipping and Transparency Flicker in Kissing Cinematic",  
  "bug_report_description": "In the hot-air-balloon kiss cutscene, individual hair strand meshes on the female lead intersect and pass through both her own facial geometry and the male lead’s head. Simultaneously, the semi-transparent hair shader repeatedly flickers – the alpha zones shift erratically each frame, causing visible popping and aliasing on the hair strands. This breaks immersion during a key emotional moment and could undermine the perceived polish of the cinematic sequence.",  
  "affected_item": "Character hair mesh / hair transparency shader"  
}

{
  "reasoning": "While advancing through the train yard the AI soldier on the far platform suddenly appears suspended in mid-air with no visible support or animation root, indicating a collision or pathfinding failure rather than normal movement. The character remains locked off the ground even when fired upon and behaves erratically until disappearing off-screen.",
  "bug_report_title": "Enemy NPC Floats in Mid-Air on Train Platform",
  "bug_report_description": "During normal play in the train yard section, an enemy AI soldier spawns or moves into a position above the train tracks but fails to collide with the ground or platform mesh. The character model remains suspended in free space without any climbing animation or visible support. The floating NPC does not react properly to player fire, continuing to hover until it eventually despawns or falls out of view. This undermines immersion, can confuse players about cover and sightlines, and may allow the AI to be unfairly targeted (or not targeted) by the player.",
  "affected_item": "NPC character collision/animation"
}

{
    "reasoning": "Midway through a highway scene the boat loaded on the trailer collides with the taxi/bike convoy, but instead of remaining attached or falling naturally, it detaches and rockets into the air as if defying gravity. The trailer and truck remain on the ground, indicating a physics and collision response error.",
    "bug_report_title": "Trailer-Mounted Boat Detaches and Flies on Collision",
    "bug_report_description": "When the player’s taxi and a pursuing motorcycle bump into a truck towing a boat trailer, the boat inexplicably snaps free from the trailer and soars skyward. The trailer and tug remain grounded, while the boat floats off at high speed, clipping through the environment and causing a distracting break in immersion. This errant physics behavior can interrupt mission flow and may leave vehicles stuck or players stranded if the collision occurs during critical chase sequences.",
    "affected_item": "physics"
}

{
  "reasoning": "An NPC drifter is sliding and floating sideways across the bar countertop in an unnatural pose. Their collision with the counter is not resolving, and ragdoll physics are activating incorrectly, causing the character to clip through and glide over the bar surface.",
  "bug_report_title": "NPC Ragdoll Slides Across Bar Counter",
  "bug_report_description": "During a conversation at the bar, an NPC drifter enters ragdoll state and becomes stuck partially inside the countertop. The character’s body clips through the bar edge and continues to glide sideways across the top of the counter rather than falling to the floor or standing up. This causes visual clipping, breaks immersion, and could potentially block player movement or disrupt scripted dialogue sequences.",
  "affected_item": "NPC physics"
}

{
    "reasoning": "During a cutscene, the NPC ‘Reiner’ appears to be suspended in mid-air rather than standing or walking on any visible surface. This unnatural floating suggests the character’s root transform or animation binding failed to snap to the ground geometry. It breaks immersion and may obscure intended camera angles or dialogue blocking.",
    "bug_report_title": "NPC Character Model Floating Above Ground During Cutscene",
    "bug_report_description": "In the dialogue sequence inside the Forest of Giant Trees, the character ‘Reiner’ is rendered hovering in mid-air instead of standing on the ground. His feet do not contact any terrain mesh, and there is no animation playing that would justify a jump or levitation. This visual anomaly persists through multiple camera cuts. The floating model not only looks out of place but also interferes with shot composition and could confuse the player about the character’s intended position or state.",
    "affected_item": "Character (Reiner) – animation/transform placement"
}

{  
  "reasoning": "The clip shows the player diving into water, sinking through the water mesh and world geometry into a bright green void, then popping back up in mid-air while still in a swim/jump animation. The water surface and seabed collision appear to be missing or misaligned, and the water shader beneath the surface renders as an unnatural green plane before the character is teleported back to the proper water level.",  
  "bug_report_title": "Player clips through water mesh into green void and is suspended in swim/jump animation",  
  "bug_report_description": "When diving into the river during the \"Lysandros' Oracle Offerings\" quest, the player character falls through the water collision and underlying terrain, ending up beneath the map in a bright green void. The water surface disappears, and the underwater shader is replaced by a flat green colour with floating foliage. After a few moments, the character is teleported back to the surface but remains in mid-air performing the swim/jump animation instead of transitioning to a normal standing pose. This clipping issue breaks immersion, hides environmental details, and can interrupt quest flow if the player cannot regain proper footing.",  
  "affected_item": "Environment geometry & water rendering/physics"  
}

{
  "reasoning": "The player character approaches a vertical vent grate that visually appears climbable, but the collision mesh is misaligned or missing climb tags. When attempting to grab and climb the grate, the character either fails to latch on or becomes stuck between the bars, sliding off the geometry instead of climbing smoothly.",
  "bug_report_title": "Misaligned Vent Grate Collision Prevents Climbing and Traps Player",
  "bug_report_description": "When the player jumps toward the vertical vent grate, the character fails to grab the bars correctly. The transition from ledge to climbing animation does not trigger, and the character’s collision capsule slips through gaps or becomes wedged between the bars. This causes the player to either fall uncontrollably or become stuck in place, blocking progress and forcing a reload or reposition. The grate visually looks climbable, but the physics collider does not match, leading to repeated failed climb attempts and potential soft-lock scenarios in that area.",
  "affected_item": "environment (vent grate collision geometry)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "During the footage Jill and the pursuing enemy both pass through and clip inside the rolling shutter door as it opens and closes. The shutter’s collision appears disabled or misaligned, allowing character models to intersect the geometry.",
    "bug_report_title": "Characters Clipping Through Partially Open Shutter",
    "bug_report_description": "When Jill approaches and moves under the partially raised metal shutter, her head and upper body clip into the shutter panel instead of stopping at its edge. Shortly thereafter, an enemy lunges through the same shutter barrier—despite it still being mostly closed—which causes the monster model to slide through the door frame improperly. This behavior indicates missing or misaligned collision on the shutter object, breaking immersion and potentially allowing unintended bypasses of the barrier.",
    "affected_item": "Environment Collision (Rolling Shutter Door)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "In the captured frames a combat helicopter hovers directly above a small outpost structure, but its rotor disk and fuselage repeatedly interpenetrate the building’s roof and tarp. The blades slice through geometry with no collision response or visual occlusion, indicating a collision-mesh or spawning-height issue rather than normal physics behavior.",
    "bug_report_title": "Helicopter clipping through roof and tarp geometry",
    "bug_report_description": "When a helicopter spawns or hovers close to the outpost building at night, its rotor blades and body clip straight through the metal roof panels and the hanging tarp. The vehicle appears to occupy the same space as static environment props, with no collision reaction (i.e., the blades visibly pass through the roof without stopping or causing any impact). This visual glitch breaks immersion and could potentially allow players to shoot enemies or be shot through unintended holes in the environment. The issue persists across multiple approaches and seems tied to an incorrect spawn altitude or missing collision meshes on the roof geometry.",
    "affected_item": "environment collision / vehicle"
}

{
    "reasoning": "During a grind attempt on a handrail, the skateboard and skater’s body clip right through the rail instead of interacting with it, then transition into an unintended ragdoll animation. The lack of collision detection causes the board to phase through geometry and the character to fall unnaturally.",
    "bug_report_title": "Handrail Collision Ignored Leading to Clipping and Ragdoll Fall",
    "bug_report_description": "When grinding the horizontal rail in the plaza section, neither the skateboard nor the skater’s body register a collision. Instead of riding along the rail, the board passes straight through it and the skater abruptly switches into a full-body ragdoll state mid-air. This results in clipping through the handrail, an unnatural tumble, and missed grind scoring. The glitch breaks immersion, prevents intended trick execution, and may disrupt combo chaining or scoring moments.",
    "affected_item": "Physics / Collision"
}

{  
  "reasoning": "In this clip, the player shoots the Tracker target through the small glass window of the incinerator. Although the shot clearly connects, the game does not immediately register the kill: the ‘Leader eliminated’ notification appears twice, the target’s silhouette reappears behind the glass, and his minimap icon remains active. The contract only completes after a second volley. These symptoms indicate that the hit-registration and death-state logic for NPCs shot through that incinerator window is failing intermittently.",  
  "bug_report_title": "Incinerator window shots fail to register kill on first hit",  
  "bug_report_description": "When the player targets the Tracker NPC through the incinerator’s viewing window and fires, the hit and ragdoll physics do not consistently trigger the NPC’s death. Instead, the kill feed (‘Leader eliminated’) flashes twice and the silhouette persists behind the glass, forcing the player to shoot again. The NPC’s minimap icon remains present and the mission objective does not update until the second successful shot. This issue disrupts gameplay flow by requiring redundant shots, confusing the player, and delaying mission completion.",  
  "affected_item": "NPC hit-registration / death-state logic"  
}

{
    "reasoning": "During the closing submission hold, the victim’s head and torso geometry repeatedly clip through both the bottom ring rope and the attacker’s hand meshes.  The rope penetrates her body in several frames and her head phase-shifts behind the rope rather than being correctly occluded, indicating broken collision and depth-sorting logic.",
    "bug_report_title": "Character & Rope Mesh Clipping During Submission Hold",
    "bug_report_description": "When the attacker applies a grounded submission (frames ~30–60), the victim’s head and upper torso intersect unnaturally with the bottom ring rope.  In some frames, the rope is rendered in front of her face when it should remain behind, and her head even passes through the attacker’s hands, resulting in visible geometry penetration.  This collision failure persists through the entire hold sequence and makes the animation look glitchy, breaking immersion and potentially confusing players about the true hitboxes during submissions.",
    "affected_item": "Character mesh / collision"
}

{  
  "reasoning": "During a melee encounter on a narrow ledge by a stone pillar, the player character clips partway through the wall, the camera blur/post-effects intensify uncontrollably, UI prompts (‘grasp’) remain onscreen, and the ‘Desynchronized – Death’ message triggers while the character is still embedded in geometry. The game then abruptly reloads memory with persistent blur rather than showing a clean death transition.",  
  "bug_report_title": "Wall-clipping triggers persistent blur and UI hang on desync death",  
  "bug_report_description": "When fighting guards on the ledge next to the stone pillar, the Assassin’s collision mesh penetrates the pillar geometry as he is struck. This causes the radial-blur and red vignette hit effect to ramp up excessively and never clear, while the on-screen action prompt (‘grasp’) and HUD icons remain active even after the death event. The ‘Desynchronized – Death’ banner appears misaligned over the stuck character, and the engine launches a memory reload without restoring camera or UI state first. This results in a jarring visual experience and may confuse players about their actual death location or status.",  
  "affected_item": "character collision/physics, camera post-processing effects, UI elements"  
}

{
  "reasoning": "As the camera switches to the overhead success view, the corrugated roof panels (and the truck’s cargo‐box roof) repeatedly pop in and out, stacking one atop another in an impossible way. This indicates a mesh or LOD streaming issue rather than intended animation.",
  "bug_report_title": "Roof panels duplicate and pop during cinematic overhead transition",
  "bug_report_description": "Immediately after completing the nightclub delivery mission, the game cuts to a top-down shot of the delivery truck. During that cinematic, the corrugated canopy (and the flat roof of the truck’s cargo box) begin to spawn duplicate geometry layers. Panels appear and disappear in sequence, stacking above the original roof, then snapping back down. This popping/ghosting of roof meshes breaks immersion, creates distracting visual artifacts, and could be symptomatic of an LOD or streaming mesh bug in the environment.",
  "affected_item": "Environment geometry (roof/canopy mesh)"
}

{
  "reasoning": "During the cutscene in the diner, the overhead monitor that’s supposed to show a clean rotating body model begins to display long, horizontal black smear artifacts and stretched shards of the character’s silhouette. This clearly isn’t intended art direction but rather a rendering/texture corruption on that screen surface.",
  "bug_report_title": "Overhead Monitor Texture Smearing/Artifacting in Diner Cutscene",
  "bug_report_description": "In the scene featuring Takemura at the diner's bar, the environmental display monitor above the counter is meant to show a simple rotating body model on a neutral background. Shortly after the conversation begins, the monitor’s shader malfunctions: black horizontal lines extend from the figure, the model’s edges stretch into shards, and the display flickers with distorted textures. This artifact continues throughout the cutscene, breaking immersion and indicating a failure in the screen’s texture/UV mapping or shader rendering process.",
  "affected_item": "Environment (Overhead Monitor/Texture Rendering)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "During the transition out of the cave area the game first shows the correct colored cave environment, then a prolonged black load screen, and on respawn the entire world is rendered in greyscale and the player’s mount is inexplicably floating high above the terrain. Both the missing color processing and the mount’s incorrect spawn position indicate rendering/shader and object‐placement failures.",
    "bug_report_title": "Post‐Load Monochrome Rendering and Mount Spawned Out of Bounds",
    "bug_report_description": "When exiting the cave and loading into Skyrim’s exterior: 1) The world is rendered entirely in greyscale (no color grading or HDR effects are applied) until another cell load. 2) The player’s horse (mount) fails to spawn at the player’s feet and instead appears locked in a static position high in the sky, unreachable. These combined issues break visual immersion, remove access to the mount, and may strand the player if dismounting is required. The bug reliably reproduces on every cave‐to‐exterior transition at this location.",
    "affected_item": "Rendering/Shader Pipeline (color grading) and Entity Spawn/Placement (mount)"
}

{
    "reasoning": "During the sequence where the player shoots the burning animal impaled on the wooden spindle, its model separates from the environment but then drifts straight upward and clips against geometry instead of falling under gravity. This behavior indicates a physics/collision anomaly.",
    "bug_report_title": "Impaled Enemy Model Floats and Clips After Detachment",
    "bug_report_description": "After firing at the creature mounted on the spinning wooden post, the enemy’s ragdoll fails to obey gravity. Instead of dropping to the ground, it floats vertically through the scene and becomes stuck against invisible collision boundaries high above the play area. This unexpected float-and-clip behavior breaks immersion and may block subsequent animations or camera angles in this scripted event.",
    "affected_item": "physics"
}

{
    "reasoning": "The Leap Attack prompt remains attached to a moving crow even after it has flown out of range, causing the player character to perform the dive on empty air and fall instead of striking the target.",
    "bug_report_title": "Leap Attack UI Persists on Moving Bird Target",
    "bug_report_description": "When targeting a crow for a Leap Attack, the combat UI marker (Y) stays visible above the bird after it takes off. The player is still able to trigger the dive animation even though the crow has moved, resulting in a missed attack and an unintended fall. This behavior interrupts gameplay flow and can lead to unexpected damage or death when executing ranged takedown actions on airborne or fleeing wildlife.",
    "affected_item": "Combat UI / Targeting System"
}

{
    "reasoning": "During the pre-race lobby sequence, the Sultan RS spawns intersecting the rotating turbine blade geometry instead of on the designated start platform. The car’s mesh is visibly clipping through the propeller and environment, indicating a collision/placement error.",
    "bug_report_title": "Vehicle Clipping Through Turbine Blade on Spawn",
    "bug_report_description": "When the race lobby loads the player’s chosen Sultan RS, the vehicle appears inside the wind turbine blade rather than snapped to the start position. The turbine propeller geometry penetrates the car’s chassis, causing severe mesh clipping. This placement bug not only looks jarring but may immobilize the player’s vehicle, preventing a fair race start or requiring a manual reposition.",
    "affected_item": "Environment collision / Vehicle spawn positioning"
}
